Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden market dynamics changes.
Other events of this kind are likely, as the global economy remains imbalanced in many ways, especially in terms of sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are at the root of most crises and present challenges for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect reliably and even more difficult to prove.
Ensuite, prédire le moment exact du point de rupture (quand les bulles éclatent, quand les marchés sont paralysés et quand il n’y a plus de crédit disponible) est, et restdera sans doute, au-delà de nos capacités d’analyse.
Enfin, les crises sont des événements fortement non linénaires qui se produisent sans signes avant-coureurs.
Les manifestations périodiques d’instabilité font payer un coût social élevé à ceux qui en sont le moins responsables.
Si ce schéma venait à se répéter, il pourrait saper la confiance dans les marchés financiers et les autorités de réglementation, une perte de confiance qui pourrait annoncer des réglementations excessives, une reprise en main de l’État et un désengagement de la mondialisation.
Mais le problème est plus grave encore.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a sovereign debt crisis for advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can translate into a dangerous fiscal imbalance characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bailout spending.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
Unbalanced situations and undetected systemic risks mean that what appear to be prudent fiscal policies may not be.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
Mais its revenues and expenditures were largely determined by a housing bubble linked to very high debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is likely a prime example of this.
In the end, the only exit is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can trigger this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, sovereign states must be vigilant to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk, and ready to take corrective measures promptly.
<s>De nouveaux cadres législatifs détaillés, mettant l’accent sur les exigences en capitaux et les effets de levier, la transparence, les notations et autres sources d’information, les incitations, les conflits d’intérêts et les limites à la taille des institutions financières, la protection des consommateurs et les mécanismes de résolution vont bientôt être adoptés.
<s>L’espoir est que ces réformes réduiront la probabilité et la sévérité des risques systémiques.
<s>Mais cela ne résoudra en rien le problème des déséquilibres mondiaux et d’autres facteurs contribuant à et annonciateurs d’instabilité.
<s>En sus et en complément de nouveaux cadres législatifs, un système de surveillance complète des risques systémiques est nécessaire.
<s>Certains politiciens et analystes de premier plan estiment toutefois qu’un tel système, visant à identifier et juguler les risques systémiques, est futile.
<s>The incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex and constantly evolving global financial system make it, according to them, either impossible or so prone to error that the effort would be futile.
Bubble assets are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we should then accept that we will periodically find ourselves in a situation of financial and fiscal instability that we cannot predict in advance.
We should also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than the one we thought necessary just three years ago.
In the realm of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one is to reject a true proposition and the other is to accept a false proposition.
Let's call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be put in these terms: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors is likely to have the highest cost?
Opponents of prudent systemic risk monitoring have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there are no reliable indicators of an increasing potential instability.
Searching for such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantly.
But this position appears fallacious.
During the 2008 crisis, for example, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note.
However, it must be admitted that these warnings were perhaps not sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the point of collapse.
They were, however, unmistakable signs.
The second position is that there are indeed warning signs, but they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that the cost of an AQF error is likely higher than an RQV error, because there are many false positive elements and/or that the remedy is worse than the problem.
There are certainly costs associated with the AQF error.
But the RQV error is also costly, as we have seen, so the aggregate negative effect of reacting to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced.
There may be a deeper trend at play.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty and errors are frequent.
The default position of advanced country policymakers seems to be, on the contrary, that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply held belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one thinks that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless there are good reasons to do so.
But given past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at best questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to design and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try this approach, and give such responsibility to a new institution, or an existing one, that has access to relevant information, possesses sharp analytical skills at both financial and macroeconomic levels, and is relatively free from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence perceptions of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby enhancing the financial system’s ability to self-regulate.
